segments.text: Of all the experiences I've had, I'm more thankful for that than anything in my whole life, really.
What were the experiences that helped to draw Aggies together?
Like, do you remember going to Silver Taps?
Oh, yeah.
Gosh, yeah.
Did you take it seriously?
Oh, yeah.
I still almost cry when I hear it.
Did your buddies?
Oh, yeah, absolutely.
And it was always respectful?
Oh, just thinking about it, I'm choking.
Do you remember going to muster?
Yeah, yeah.
I went to several, not many.
I've never been to one locally.
One that I wished I could have gone to was 10 years ago this year, the survivors of the Corregidor Muster were back on campus.
Oh my gosh.
Don't I wish I could have heard their stories.
Oh gosh, yeah.
You're seeing your ring.
How much did it cost?
Do you remember?
I bought two.
I bought one for her and one for me.
I bought hers and mine.
And I don't wear it very often.
It still looks new because when I was cutting meat, you know, I just wear it when I go out, you know.
I don't remember.
You've never lost it?
No.
Do you have any ring stories where somebody somewhere in some faraway place noticed something?
Oh, yeah, yeah.
I don't remember the stories, you know, but yeah, people notice it.
Why is an Aggie ring so precious?
I think people know how we feel about it maybe, and it just kind of comes out, you know.
Because whenever you get any comments, you know, they're pretty well aware of it.
Is the spirit still there?
Oh, yes.
Oh, yes.
Even with the civilians, the non-regs?
And the women may have more pride than the men.
Well, women are good about that.
Yes, yes.
You know, they are.
Yes.
All right.
You stayed in the Corps.
through your fifth semester.
Yeah, let's see.
Yeah.
And then got out.
Where did you live then as a non-reg?
In dorm 12, or was it?
OK. You lived on campus?
Those dorms that were numbered.
You lived on campus?
Yeah.
Oh, yes, on campus.
Sure.
Now, the fact that you had been in the Corps and were then a non-reg, did that matter in terms of friendships and acceptance and everything?
No, no.
And my roommate that I had while I was a non-reg had the same problem.
And so he had been in the Corps.
And I knew him from before.
So you didn't buy senior boots.
No.
And you didn't get to go through final review.
No.
Commencement.
You attended commencement.
Oh, yes.
All right.
You're not yet married, but now you're serious.
By the time you're graduating, are you serious with that young man?
Yeah.
Who came to commencement when you graduated?
A cousin of mine that was...
I always thought he was an uncle because he was so much older than I was, but he was a cousin and my brother, the only two that came.
This special young lady didn't come?
No.
Well, she was still in school.
And mom and dad didn't come?
No.
Well, my mother had died.
My mother died in May.
She died in 49, but I don't remember, February, March.
She had a heart problem.
And then daddy had the store, you know.
He couldn't come, but he sent my cousin and my brother came.
And they were impressed.
Do you remember where commencement was held?
No.
I think it was outside.
All right.
In that era, many times they were held at the football stadium.
Yeah.
I think that's where it was.
Every name was called.
Every hand was shaken.
Every hand was shaken.
Even mine.
What is it that builds this pride, this spirit, this feeling of Iagish?
I think it starts at the beginning.
And it builds as you go, as you see the things that happen and the things you do and the things they tell you.
And it just gets stronger and stronger and stronger as you go.
And even when you leave, it gets stronger when you see what it's done for you, what it's done for me.
I don't know about everybody else.
It's, you know, it's there.
And you never thought about transferring anywhere else?
No.
I went to school one summer here just to get some extra so I could graduate with the class.
You know, I was a spring, I was a frog.
So I went to school and carried, I think, six or nine hours here and transferred them.
And that way I graduated in June of 49 with the rest of the fish, you know.
If you were a consultant today,
to the leadership of A&M about A&M's future, what would you urge them to do?
I don't keep up with it much, but I would say the way they're growing and everything is just keep doing what you're doing.
You say the spirit's still there.
It's just that many more people that are getting it, and it should be good for the country.
I don't know of anything that they could do that would make it any better.
It keeps growing.
It keeps getting better.
The spirit's still there.
I don't know.
If you could make a major gift to Texas A&M,
Somebody walks up to you, hands you a check for a million dollars, and there's only one restriction.
You must give it to Texas A&M.
What would you want your gift used for?
I don't know.
I don't know.
Just offhand, I'd say maybe set up a scholarship or two or three or four for troubled guys that could go there and be in the Corps
and go through the Aggie system.
I think it would- Now troubled, how do you mean by troubled?
Well delinquents maybe, guys that maybe could have been good, guys that grew up without a father, all these people that I think A&M would really, really help.
To what people related to A&M, students, faculty, or whatever, do you feel the most gratitude as you look back?
To whom are you most grateful?
Oh, my upperclassmen.
Yeah, really and truly.
And most of them were really good, I learned from them all, they all had good attitudes, and I always thought they were fair.
Even when they were beating on me I thought I had it coming.
I think my upperclassmen.
All right, I've only got one more question.
What have we not covered that we should have?
Do you have any, had you thought of any stories or things you wanted to be sure to?
No, no.
The only thing, we didn't go into detail was my romance, you know, but I don't think that's relative to this, you know.
All right, then the last question is, what feelings do you hold in your heart today for Texas A&M?
mostly gratitude for what it did for me.
I don't do much to show it.
I do the silver thing every year.
And that's it.
That's all I do.
But I feel gratitude.
Just thank the Lord every day that something took me there.
You know, I don't know what.
But that's it.
That's a good ending.
